  <article xml:id="session2wks" label="1052">
    <title>MATH 142 Hands-On, Grades Up</title>
    <introduction>
    <p>
     For workspace between exercises, print this worksheet or download to your device by clicking the printer icon.
    </p>
    </introduction>
<!--START TYPING CONTENT FOR SESSION BELOW HERE-->
<worksheet>
    <title> Session #2 (Sections 1.3-1.4)</title><!-- SECTION 1-->
    
    <p>
      Directions: Answer each of the following as best you can. Feel free to discuss your thoughts about the questions with some peers around you. 
      For additional practice problems and explanations, refer to the Math 142 textbook which is free and can be downloaded as a PDF 
      at <url href="https://oaktrust.library.tamu.edu/items/03980291-5e85-4d2e-a742-961ac49666aa"> Texas A&amp;M The OAKTrust Digital Repository </url>.
    </p>
      <paragraphs>
        <title>Getting Warmed Up and in the Right Mindset</title>
    <exercise workspace="2.5in"><!-- #1 -->
      <statement>
        <p>
          Given <m>\displaystyle {\lim_{x\rightarrow \infty} f(x) = 4}</m> and <m>\D {\lim_{x\rightarrow -\infty} f(x) = -2}</m>,
           what do you then know about any horizontal asymptotes of <m>f(x)</m>?
        </p>
      </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise workspace="2.5in"><!-- #2 -->
      <statement>
        <p>
        Given the following information about <m>g(x)</m>, what do you know about the horizontal and vertical asymptotes? 
        <md>
           <mrow> \D{\lim_{x\rightarrow \infty} g(x) \rightarrow \infty},
            \D{\lim_{x\rightarrow -\infty} g(x) \rightarrow \infty},
            \D{\lim_{x\rightarrow 2^+} g(x) \rightarrow \infty},</mrow>
            <mrow>\D{\lim_{x\rightarrow 2^-} g(x) \rightarrow -\infty}, 
            \D{\lim_{x\rightarrow 5} g(x) \rightarrow \infty}</mrow>
        </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    
    
    <exercise workspace="4.1in"><!-- #3 -->
      <statement>
        <p>
            Determine each of the following limits.
            Input the functions into your graphing calculator if you prefer a graphical view to find the limits.
            <tabular>
            <row>
                <cell>(a) <m>\D{\lim_{x\rightarrow \infty} \frac{1}{x}}</m> </cell>
                <cell />
                <cell>(b) <m>\D{\lim_{x\rightarrow -\infty} \frac{1}{x}}</m> </cell>
                <cell />
                <cell>(c) <m>\D{\lim_{x\rightarrow \infty} \frac{4}{x^{3}}}</m> </cell>
            </row>

            <row>
                <cell />
                <cell />
                <cell />
                <cell />
                <cell />
            </row>

            <row>
                <cell>(d) <m>\D{\lim_{x\rightarrow -\infty} e^x}</m> </cell>
                <cell />
                <cell>(e)<m>\D{\lim_{x\rightarrow \infty} e^{-x}}</m> </cell>
                <cell />
                <cell>(f) <m>\D{\lim_{x\rightarrow -\infty} e^{7x}}</m> </cell>
                <cell />
                <cell />
            </row>

            <row>
                <cell>(g) <m>\D{\lim_{x\rightarrow -\infty} 5e^{-6x}}</m> </cell>
                <cell />
                <cell>(h) <m>\D{\lim_{x\rightarrow \infty} e^{8x}}</m> </cell>
                <cell />
                <cell>(i) <m>\D{\lim_{x\rightarrow -\infty} 5e^{-6x}}</m> </cell>
                <cell />
                <cell />
                <cell />
                <cell />
                <cell />
                <cell />
            </row>
            </tabular>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise><!-- #4 -->
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Examine the limits above, group them together by finding patterns or common characteristics, then fill in the blanks below.
          Some are already filled in for you.
        </p>
      </introduction>
            <task>
                <p>
                Given <m>\D f(x)=\frac{c}{x^{n}}</m> where <m>c</m> is any real number and <m>n>0</m> then 
                <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\rightarrow \infty}f(x)\,\stackrel{\textstyle =0}{\rule{0.75in}{0.05mm}}</m> 
                and <m>\D{\lim_{x\rightarrow -\infty} f(x) } \rule{1in}{0.05mm}</m>.
                </p>
              </task>

            <task>
                <p>
                Given <m>\D g(x)= e^{nx}</m> where and <m>n>0</m> then <m>\D{\lim_{x\rightarrow \infty} g(x)}\,\stackrel{\textstyle \to \infty}{\rule{0.75in}{0.05mm}}</m> 
                and <m>\D{\lim_{x\rightarrow -\infty} g(x)} \rule{1in}{0.05mm}</m>.
                </p>
              </task>

            <task>
                <p>
                Given <m>\D h(x)= e^{-nx}</m> where and <m>n>0</m> then <m>\D{\lim_{x\rightarrow \infty} h(x)}\,\stackrel{\textstyle =0}{\rule{0.75in}{0.05mm}}</m> 
                and <m>\D{\lim_{x\rightarrow -\infty} h(x)} \rule{1in}{0.05mm}</m>.
                </p>
              </task>
    </exercise> 
    </paragraphs> 

    <paragraphs>
        <title>Let Us Get Our Hands On</title>
    <exercise number="1"><!-- #1 -->
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Find any (a) horizontal asymptotes, (b) the coordinates of any holes, and (c) vertical asymptotes of the function.
          If there are no horizontal asymptotes, describe the end behavior using limit notation.
        </p>
      </introduction>
        <task workspace="1.7in"> <m>\D h(x)=\frac{(x-4)(x+3)}{(x+4)(x-4)(8x+3)}=\frac{x^{2}-x-12}{8x^{3}+3x^{2}-128x-48}</m> </task>
        <task workspace="1.7in"> <m>\D f(x)=\frac{(3x+5)(x+2)}{4(x+2)^{2}}=\frac{3x^{2}+11x+10}{4x^{2}+16x+16}</m> </task> 
        <task workspace="1.7in"> <m>\D f(x)=\frac{x(x-5)(x+5)}{x^{2}+8x+15}=\frac{x^{3}-25x}{x^{2}+8x+15}</m> </task>
    </exercise> 
    
    
    <exercise number="2"><!-- #2 -->
      <introduction>
        <p>
        Given <m>\D f(x)=\frac{4-e^{-2x}}{3e^{-2x}+1}</m>, follow the steps below to find the horizontal asymptotes of <m>f</m>, if any exist.
        </p>
      </introduction>
        <task workspace="1.5in">
            <p>
            Set up but do not yet solve the two limits that are needed to determine the horizontal asymptotes.
            </p>
        </task>
        <task>
            <p>
            Fill in the blanks with either <em>positive</em> or <em>negative</em>.
            <ol marker="i.">
                <li>
                <p>
                    <em>If <m>x \to \infty</m>, we divide all terms by the <m>e^{nx}</m> in the denominator that has the most <m>\rule{0.75in}{0.05mm} </m> power.</em>
                </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                <p>
                    <em>If <m>x \to -\infty</m>, we divide all terms by the <m>e^{nx}</m> in the denominator that has the most <m>\rule{0.75in}{0.05mm} </m> power.</em>
                </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
            </p>
        </task>
        <task workspace="3.5in">
            <p>
            Apply the techniques from part(b) to compute the limits in part(a) and state the horizontal asymptotes of <m>f</m>.
            If there are none, describe the end behavior using limit notation.
            It may help to refer to problem 4 from the “Getting Warmed Up and In the Right Mindset” section.
            </p>
          </task>
    </exercise>
    
    
    <exercise number="3"><!-- #3 -->
      <statement>
        <p> 
        Below is an outline of the Definition of Continuity at a Point.
        Fill in the blanks below to correctly complete the text in the definition.
        <url href="https://oaktrust.library.tamu.edu/items/03980291-5e85-4d2e-a742-961ac49666aa">The Math 142 textbook</url> has some very good references to help better understand continuity.
        See pages 124-131 for definitions, examples, and step-by-step instructions.
        <p>
        A function <m>f</m> is <term>continuous at a point </term> where <m>x = c</m> if and only if the following three conditions are satisfied: 
        <ol marker="I.">
        <li><m>\rule{0.75in}{0.05mm} </m> is defined.</li>
        <li><m>\rule{0.75in}{0.05mm} </m> exists.</li>
        <li><m>\displaystyle\lim_{x \rightarrow c} f(x) = \rule{0.75in}{0.05mm}</m> </li>
        </ol>
        </p>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise> 
    <exercise workspace="1in" number="4"><!-- #4 -->
      <statement>
        <p> 
        If you know <m>\D \lim_{x\rightarrow 2}g(x) = 4</m> and <m>g(2)=7</m>, can you correctly conclude that <m>g(x)</m> continuous at <m>x=2</m>? Why or why not?
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise> 
    
    <exercise number="5"><!-- #5 -->
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Use the graph of <m>f(x)</m> to determine if <m>f(x)</m> is continuous at <m>x=-2</m>.
          <image source="MATH142_HOGU_Session2_Fig1.png" width="50%">
            <shortdescription> Graph of a function plotted on the coordinate axes. Refer to image description for more detail.</shortdescription>
            <description>
              <p> Graph of a function <m>f(x)</m> plotted on the coordinate axes. 
                The graph increases from the bottom left until it reaches a peak at <m>(-4,5)</m> and then decreases until it hits the point <m>(-2, 1)</m>.
                The graph then picks up again at the point <m>(-2,-4)</m> where it decreases to the point <m>(-2,-4)</m>, where it then increases until it leaves the 
                coordinate axes on the top right.
                The graph has a closed circle at <m>(-2,1)</m> and an open circle at <m>(-2,-4)</m>.</p>
            </description>
          </image>
        </p>
      </introduction>
            <task workspace="0.5in">
              <p>
                Is <m>\D f(-2)</m> defined? If so, find the value.
              </p>
            </task>
            <task workspace="0.5in">
              <p>
                Does <m>\D{\lim_{x\rightarrow -2} f(x)}</m> exist? If so, find the value.
              </p>
            </task>
            <task workspace="0.5in">
              <p>
                Does <m>\displaystyle{\lim_{x \rightarrow -2} f(x) =f(-2)}</m>?
              </p>
            </task>
            <task workspace="0.5in">
              <p>
                Is <m>f(x)</m> is continuous at <m>x=-2</m>? If not, at what condition (I, II, or III) does it fail first?              
              </p>
            </task>
    </exercise> 
    
    
    <exercise number="6"><!-- #6 -->
      <introduction>
        <p> 
          Use the graph of <m>f(x)</m> to determine if <m>f(x)</m> is continuous at <m>x=-2</m>.
          <image source="MATH142_HOGU_Session2_Fig2.png" width="50%">
          <shortdescription> Graph of a function plotted on the coordinate axes. Refer to image description for more detail.</shortdescription>
            <description>
              <p>Graph of a function <m>f(x)</m> plotted on the coordinate axes. 
                The graph increases from the bottom left until it reaches a peak at <m>(-4,5)</m> and then decreases until it hits the point <m>(-1, 0)</m>, then increases 
                until it leaves the coordinate axes on the top right.
                The graph has an open circle at <m>(-2,1)</m>.</p>
            </description>
          </image>
        </p>
      </introduction>
            <task workspace="0.5in">
              <p>
                Is <m>\D f(-2)</m> defined? If so, find the value.
              </p>
            </task>
            <task workspace="0.5in">
              <p>
                Does <m>\D{\lim_{x\rightarrow -2} f(x)}</m> exist? If so, find the value.
              </p>
            </task>
            <task workspace="0.5in">
              <p>
                Does <m>\displaystyle{\lim_{x \rightarrow -2} f(x) =f(-2)}</m>?
              </p>
            </task>
            <task workspace="0.5in">
              <p>
                Is <m>f(x)</m> is continuous at <m>x=-2</m>? If not, at what condition (I, II, or III) does it fail first? 
              </p>
            </task>
    </exercise> 

    <exercise number="7"><!-- #7 -->
      <introduction>
        <p> 
          Use the graph of <m>h(x)</m> to determine if <m>h(x)</m> is continuous at <m>x=-2</m>.
          <image source="MATH142_HOGU_Session2_Fig3.png" width="50%">
          <shortdescription> Graph of a function plotted on the coordinate axes. Refer to image description for more detail.</shortdescription>
            <description>
              <p>Graph of a function <m>h(x)</m> plotted on the coordinate axes. 
                The graph increases from the bottom left until it reaches a peak at <m>(-4,5)</m> and then decreases until it hits the point <m>(-1, 0)</m>, then increases 
                until it leaves the coordinate axes on the top right.
                The graph has an open circle at <m>(-2,1)</m> and a closed circle at <m>(-2,6)</m>.</p>
            </description>
          </image>
        </p>
      </introduction>
            <task workspace="0.5in">
              <p>
                Is <m>\D h(-2)</m> defined? If so, find the value.
              </p>
            </task>
            <task workspace="0.5in">
              <p>
                Does <m>\D{\lim_{x\rightarrow -2} h(x)}</m> exist? If so, find the value.
              </p>
            </task>
            <task workspace="0.5in">
              <p>
                Does <m>\displaystyle{\lim_{x \rightarrow -2} h(x) =h(-2)}</m>?
              </p>
            </task>
            <task workspace="0.5in">
              <p>
                Is <m>h(x)</m> is continuous at <m>x=-2</m>? If not, at what condition (I, II, or III) does it fail first? 
              </p>
            </task>
    </exercise> 
    
    
    <exercise number="8"><!-- #8 -->
      <introduction>
        <p> 
          Use the graph of <m>p(x)</m> to determine if <m>p(x)</m> is continuous at <m>x=3</m>.
          <image source="MATH142_HOGU_Session2_Fig4.png" width="50%">
          <shortdescription> Graph of a function plotted on the coordinate axes. Refer to image description for more detail.</shortdescription>
            <description>
              <p>Graph of a function <m>p(x)</m> plotted on the coordinate axes.
                Starting on the left, the graph increases away from, but never touches, the <m>x</m>-axis, reaching a vertical asymptote of <m>x = 3</m>.
                The graph then decreases to the right of the vertical asymptote, approaching but not touching the <m>x</m>-axis until it leaves the coordinate axes.
              </p>
            </description>
          </image>
        </p>
      </introduction>
            <task workspace="0.5in">
              <p>
                Is <m>\D p(3)</m> defined? If so, find the value.
              </p>
            </task>
            <task workspace="0.5in">
              <p>
                Does <m>\D{\lim_{x\rightarrow 3} p(x)}</m> exist? If so, find the value.
              </p>
            </task>
            <task workspace="0.5in">
              <p>
                Does <m>\displaystyle{\lim_{x \rightarrow 3} p(x) =p(3)}</m>?
              </p>
            </task>
            <task workspace="0.5in">
              <p>
                Is <m>p(x)</m> is continuous at <m>x=3</m>? If not, at what condition (I, II, or III) does it fail first? 
              </p>
            </task>
    </exercise> 

    <exercise number="9"><!-- #9 -->
      <introduction>
        <p> 
          Use the graph of <m>t(x)</m> to determine if <m>t(x)</m> is continuous at <m>x=-4</m>.
          <image source="MATH142_HOGU_Session2_Fig5.png" width="50%">
          <shortdescription> Graph of a function plotted on the coordinate axes. Refer to image description for more detail.</shortdescription>
            <description>
              <p>Graph of a piece-wise function <m>t(x)</m> plotted on the coordinate axes.
                Staring on the bottom left, the graph in linear and increases until it reaches a peak at <m>(-4,2)</m> and then decreases to the point <m>(1,-3)</m>.
                The graph is then a horizontal line with endpoints <m>(1,-2)</m> and <m>(3,-2)</m>, and then forms the top of a semicircle with endpoints <m>(3,-2)</m>
                and <m>(5,-2)</m>. 
                The graph then increases and is linear from the point <m>(5,-2)</m> until it leaves the coordinate axes on the top right.
                The graph has closed circles at <m>(1,-2)</m> and <m>(5,1)</m>, and the graph has open circles at <m>(1,-3)</m> and <m>(5,-2)</m>.
              </p>
            </description>
          </image>
        </p>
      </introduction>
            <task workspace="0.5in">
              <p>
                Is <m>\D t(-4)</m> defined? If so, find the value.
              </p>
            </task>
            <task workspace="0.5in">
              <p>
                Does <m>\D{\lim_{x\rightarrow -4} t(x)}</m> exist? If so, find the value.
              </p>
            </task>
            <task workspace="0.5in">
              <p>
                Does <m>\displaystyle{\lim_{x \rightarrow -4} t(x) =t(-4)}</m>?
              </p>
            </task>
            <task workspace="0.5in">
              <p>
                Is <m>t(x)</m> is continuous at <m>x=-4</m>? If not, at what condition (I, II, or III) does it fail first? 
              </p>
            </task>
    </exercise> 
  
  
    <exercise number="10"><!-- #10 -->
      <introduction>
        <p> 
          Determine the intervals of continuity for each function below.
          <url href="https://oaktrust.library.tamu.edu/items/03980291-5e85-4d2e-a742-961ac49666aa">Page 126 of your textbook</url> 
          has a list of domain restrictions that will help find the intervals of continuity for functions in symbolic form.
        </p>
      </introduction>
          
            <task workspace="3in">
              <p>
                <m>\D f(x)=\sqrt{5x-7}</m>
              </p>
            </task>

            <task workspace="3in">
              <p>
                <m>\D g(x)=\frac{(x+2)(x-3)}{(x+4)(x+2)}</m>
              </p>
            </task>

              <task workspace="3in">
                <p>
                  <m>\D h(x)=\log_{3}(8+2x)</m>
                </p>
              </task>

              <task workspace="3in">
                <p>
                  <m>\D p(x)=5x^{4}+10x^{3}-15x^{2}</m>
                </p>
              </task>

              <task workspace="4in">
                <p>
                  Given <m>\displaystyle f(x)= \begin{cases}5^{3x+6}&#x26;x \leq -2\\ \\ \displaystyle \frac{x^2-x}{x^2+x}&#x26;x>-2 \\\end{cases}</m>
                </p>
              </task>
            
    </exercise> 
  </paragraphs>
  
    <paragraphs>
        <title>Now Grades Go Up</title>
      <p>
      Use the graph of <m> f(x) </m> to answer questions #1-3.
      <image source="MATH142_HOGU_Session2_Fig6.png" width="60%">
        <shortdescription>Graph of a function plotted on the coordinate axes. Refer to image description for more detail.</shortdescription>
        <description>
          <p>
            Graph of a piece-wise function <m>f(x)</m> plotted on the coordinate axes. 
            Starting on the left, the graph decreases and is linear until the point <m>(-2,1)</m> and then forms a parabola with endpoints <m>(-2,1)</m> and <m>(2,1)</m> 
            and vertex <m>(0,5)</m>.
            The graph is then a horizontal line from <m>(2,2)</m> to <m>(4,2)</m>.
            After the point <m>(4,2)</m>, the graph increases and reaches a peak between <m>x=6</m> and <m>x=7</m> before dipping slightly and increases again after <m>x=9</m>
            and leaving the coordinate axes.
            The graph has closed circles at <m>(-1,6)</m> and <m>(2,2)</m>, and open circles at <m>(-1,4)</m>, <m>(2,1)</m>, and <m>(4,2)</m>.
          </p>
        </description>
      </image>
      </p>
      <exercise workspace ="1in" number="1"><!-- #1 -->
        <statement>
          <p>
            The graph of <m>f(x)</m> is not continuous at <m>x=2</m> because <fillin/> 
            <ol marker="I.">
            <li><m>f(2)</m> is not defined.</li>
            <li><m>\D{\lim_{x\rightarrow 2} f(x)}</m> does not exist.</li>
            <li><m>f(2) \neq \D{\lim_{x\rightarrow 2} f(x)}.</m></li>
            </ol>
            <ol marker="(a)">
              <li> I and III only </li>
              <li> III only </li>
              <li> II and III only </li>
              <li> I, II, and III </li>
              <li> II only </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise workspace ="2in" number="2"><!-- #2 -->
        <statement>
          <p>
            Which of the following is true regarding the horizontal asymptotes for <m>\D g(x)=\frac{3e^{3x}-5}{7e^{2x}+8}</m>?
            <ol marker="(a)">
              <li><m>g(x)</m> does not have any horizontal asymptotes. </li>
              <li> <m>g(x)</m> has two horizontal asymptotes; one at <m>\D y=\frac{3}{7}</m> and another at <m>\D y=-\frac{5}{8}</m>. </li>
              <li> <m>g(x)</m> has only one horizontal asymptotes at <m>\D y=\frac{3}{7}</m>. </li>
              <li> <m>g(x)</m> has only one horizontal asymptotes at <m>\D y=-\frac{5}{8}</m>. </li>
              <li> <m>g(x)</m> has two horizontal asymptotes; one at <m>\D y=0</m> and another at <m>\D y=\frac{3}{7}</m>. </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>


      <exercise workspace ="1in" number="3"><!-- #3 -->
        <statement>
          <p>
            Suppose for some function <m>g(x)</m>, you know <m>\D{\lim_{x\rightarrow 3^-} g(x) \rightarrow -\infty}</m>.
            What can you conclude happens at <m>x=3</m>?
            <ol marker="(a)">
              <li> <m>g(x)</m> has a vertical asymptote at <m>x=3</m>. </li>
              <li> <m>g(x)</m> has a horizontal asymptote at <m>x=3</m>. </li>
              <li> <m>\D{\lim_{x\rightarrow -\infty} g(x) =-3}</m>.</li>
              <li> <m>g(x)</m> has a hole at <m>x=3</m>. </li>
              <li> <m>g(3)=\infty</m> </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      </paragraphs>

  </worksheet>

  </article>

